    slug: 'four-temperaments',
    title: 'The Four Temperaments',
    category: 'Constitution',
    summary: 'Choleric, sanguine, melancholic, and phlegmatic — Steiner\'s understanding of temperament as the meeting point of cosmic inheritance and individual biography.',
    readMinutes: 4,
    body: `The four temperaments — choleric, sanguine, phlegmatic, and melancholic — are ancient categories that Steiner placed on a rigorous spiritual-scientific basis. They are not personality types in the contemporary psychological sense; they describe the particular way in which a person's karmic inheritance (the qualities of their Ego from previous lives) has encountered the biological inheritance of their parents.

The choleric temperament corresponds to the element of fire. The choleric will-nature drives through obstacles. The dominant member is the Ego working powerfully on the astral body. When this strength is one-sided, it produces irritability and an intolerance of opposition. The gift is purposeful initiative; the shadow is the will to dominate. The practice for the choleric is equanimity — learning to carry the fire without burning everything around them.

The sanguine corresponds to air. The sanguine moves quickly through impressions, receives many and holds few. The astral body is dominant, shifting the Ego from one vivid experience to the next. The gift is lightness, sociability, and fresh perception; the shadow is superficiality and an inability to sustain effort. The practice is persistence — returning deliberately to what has been left.

The melancholic corresponds to water. The physical body weighs more heavily on the melancholic; experience is felt deeply and retained long. Sensitivity is the gift; brooding, self-enclosed suffering is the shadow. The practice is positivity — not forced optimism, but the deliberate cultivation of what is true and nourishing.

The phlegmatic corresponds to earth. The etheric body is dominant; inner processes run deep and slow. The gift is steadiness, calm, and a genuine comfort in physical life. The shadow is inertia and a resistance to what demands inner movement. The practice is will-training: arbitrary acts that awaken the sleeping will.

In practice, every person is a mixture, with one or two temperaments predominating. Steiner suggested that rather than fighting one's temperament, the most productive approach is to work with its specific gifts while developing the counter-practice that prevents its characteristic degeneration.`,
