    slug: 'cosmic-year',
    title: 'The Cosmic Year and Its Thresholds',
    category: 'Seasons',
    summary: 'The four threshold festivals of the cosmic year — Easter, St John\'s, Michaelmas, Christmas — as cosmic events in the life of the earth and the human soul.',
    readMinutes: 4,
    body: `Steiner spoke of the Earth as a living organism that breathes with the rhythm of the year: exhaling from Easter to Michaelmas as its soul-forces expand outward into the periphery, and inhaling from Michaelmas to Easter as those forces contract back into the core. This is not a metaphor but a description of observable seasonal changes in the quality of consciousness and in the activity of the elemental beings associated with the earth's vegetation.

Easter marks the beginning of the year's outbreath. The resurrection quality of Easter — new life pressing through death — is cosmic, not only biographical. The earth's soul rises toward the sun. This is the season of spring: the forces of growth press outward, and human beings are naturally drawn into the world. Thinking becomes more receptive, feeling becomes more expansive. The risk of the spring is that the ego dissolves somewhat into the surrounding world and loses its own centre.

St John's Day, June 24, marks the peak of the outbreath. At midsummer, the earth's soul is furthest from its own centre, most expanded into the cosmos. Steiner associated St John's with fire festivals and with the fullest exposure of the ego to cosmic forces. The question at midsummer is: who am I when I am most fully in the world?

Michaelmas, September 29, marks the turning point — the beginning of the inbreath. The Archangel Michael is associated with the iron quality of will, with the sword that cuts through what is merely habitual, and with the courage required to face one's own spiritual situation honestly. The Michael season runs from mid-August to mid-November, and its characteristic quality is one of sobriety, sharpness, and inner challenge. The Michael question is not "How do you feel?" but "What are you doing?"

Christmas marks the depth of the inbreath: the earth's soul is most contracted, most intensely spiritual in its core. In the longest darkness of the year, a new sun is born — the light that is invisible to physical eyes. The Holy Nights (December 25–January 6) are a time of intensified dreaming and spiritual receptivity, when the boundary between the living and the dead is thin and karmic encounters often arise.

These four thresholds are not artificial divisions of a continuous year but real spiritual events that any attentive practitioner can perceive — not necessarily as visions, but as changes in the quality of inner life as the year progresses.`,
