    category: 'Spiritual Science',
    summary: 'We live in the epoch governed by the Archangel Michael — an age of spiritual courage, free thinking, and the Christianisation of the intellect.',
    readMinutes: 4,
    body: `The Archangel Michael became the leading Time Spirit — the Archangel governing the spiritual direction of the present epoch — around 1879. Steiner described each epoch (lasting approximately 350 years) as governed by one of seven Archangels in rotation. The Michael epoch began with a battle in the spiritual world: Michael defeated the Ahrimanic dragon and cast it down into the realm of humanity, where its materialistic influence intensified in the form of scientific materialism.

The Michael impulse is therefore not comfortable or sentimental. It is the impulse of spiritual courage — the capacity to think freely about spiritual realities without hiding behind religious authority or scientific convention. The Michael Age asks each person to take personal responsibility for their spiritual development: to think for themselves, to test what they receive against their own experience, and to act from inner conviction rather than external command.

The sword of Michael is the transformed intellect. The intellect that merely analyses and separates — the Ahrimanic intellect — becomes Michaelic when it is taken hold of by the Ego and directed toward the perception of spiritual realities. This is not a rejection of thinking but its transformation. The Michaelic thinker does not abandon rigour; they extend rigour into domains that materialism has declared off-limits.

The Michael community, in Steiner's teaching, consists of those human beings — from every tradition and background — who were prepared in the spiritual world before their current incarnation specifically for this task: to carry free spiritual thinking into the culture of the present age. This preparation included attendance at cosmic imaginations in the Michael school between death and re-birth, in which the Sophia — the world-wisdom — was transmitted as a living force rather than a doctrine.

Practically speaking, the Michael Age places specific demands on the practitioner. The old path of initiation through grades, oaths, and institutional authority is replaced by a path of individual inner responsibility: the Threshold is crossed alone, in full daylight consciousness, with no external authority to guarantee the results. This is more demanding than older forms of initiation. It is also, in the Michaelic sense, more human.`,
